article.description: Walker scored 33 points, including the winning 3-pointer in the final minute, and Paul Pierce had 40, leading the Boston Celtics to a come-from-behind 100-99 victory over Philadelphia.

related.description: Antoine Walker is expected to miss at least one game with a knee injury sustained in the Boston Celtics' comeback victory over the Philadelphia 76ers.

article.headline: Sixers blow 20-point halftime lead, C's duo delivers
article.linkText: Pierce leads Celtics from 23 down, toppling Sixers
article.story:
PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Antoine Walker didn't let a sore knee affect his shooting.
Walker

Pierce

Walker scored 33 points, including the winning 3-pointer in the final minute, and Paul Pierce had 40, leading the Boston Celtics to a 100-99 comeback victory over the Philadelphia 76ers on Monday night. Boston, which trailed by 23 early in the third quarter, has won four in a row. "Walker has a pretty sore knee so my response was to play him (46) minutes,'' Celtics coach Jim O'Brien said. "I told him it would keep warm that way.'' Allen Iverson had 29 points, and Eric Snow added 17 for the Sixers, who have lost eight of 10. Walker's 3-pointer with 30 seconds left gave the Celtics a one-point lead. The Sixers had three chances to win it in the final seconds, but Aaron McKie missed a shot and Snow missed two, including a 19-footer before the buzzer. "We had good looks,'' Sixers coach Larry Brown said. "We're not making plays. That's why we're losing.'' Pierce scored 26 in the second half, and finished 13-for-26. Walker had 19 in the second half, and shot 12-for-24. The Celtics were 22-for-34 in the final two quarters. Boston played without two starters, center Tony Battie and guard Tony Delk. Battie missed his fourth straight game with a sore right knee. Delk sat out his second in a row with a sprained left ankle. "We're a resilient group,'' Pierce said. "We never give up. Most teams down 20 against a team like Philly wouldn't come back. You've got to bury us in a grave to stop us from coming back.'' A jumper by Pierce gave the Celtics their first lead, 95-94 with 3:16 left. Pierce then hit a 20-footer to make it 97-94. But with the shot clock winding down, Snow hit a long 3-pointer to tie it, then made a crisp bounce pass to McKie for a driving layup that gave the Sixers a 99-97 lead with 1:06 left. Walker then hit his sixth 3 to put the Celtics ahead to stay. Walker didn't speak to reporters after the game because he was in the training room icing his knee. "This is bad,'' Iverson said. "A game like this could ruin a team's confidence. To give up a 20-point lead at home, this is sad. There's no excuse for it.'' Boston went on runs of 14-0 and 11-0 in the third quarter, tying the game on a 3-pointer by Pierce with one second left in the third. Snow, who shot 63.4 percent (33-for-52) in his previous five games, missed his first five shots before hitting a 17-footer with 5:38 left. He was 12-for-12 from the foul line. The Sixers outscored Boston 17-6 over the last 6:14 of the second quarter to take a 58-38 halftime lead. The Celtics missed their last 10 shots in the first half. "Our guys never think they are out of a game,'' O'Brien said.

Game notes
The Sixers had won 14 of the last 18 against the Celtics, excluding the playoffs. Boston beat Philadelphia in five games in a first-round series last spring. ... Boston got a technical foul for a defensive 3-second violation just 11 seconds into the game. ... Iverson's 23-foot jumper in the second quarter gave him 12,000 points in his career. ... Boston's bench didn't score until the fourth. ... The Sixers are 6-16 since a 15-4 start. ... Snow's 12 free throws made and attempted were career-highs.
